Subject: Sacred food as offering 
To: Jean
Content:
A very recent realm of anthropology is the study of sacred food, which is one of the most important elements of many religions. All religions have prescriptions about the correct preparation and cooking of food, besides the taboos about forbidden subjects (for instance, animals for hinduism, pork for judaism and islamism, etc.). Many religions have special spellings for the food, which sacralize it and, therefore, who will eat it; but there are foods sacred by its inner nature. In Brazilian candombl by example, fishes are sacred for their connection to Iemanj, horns given the relation to Ians. Consequently those foods are considered offerings. This takes place in other religions too. Some examples: 
